{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":13535,"record_hash":"sha256:f34c6bf627c90dcac183198eced4242a81388540e38947a0ba39d8c74fa1c3f7","timestamp":"2026-05-07T22:25:58.127Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yep. The crate is basically a narrow pipeline. The only public surface is:\n\n```text\nbut crate\n  -> but_agentlog::Command\n  -> but_agentlog::run_from_current_dir(...)\n```\n\nEverything else is private/internal.\n\n```text\nCLI args\n  |\n  v\nCommand::Capture\n  agent: String\n  transcript_path: PathBuf\n  target: String\n  |\n  v\nrun_from_current_dir(...)\n  - parse agent string into Agent\n  - discover/canonicalize repo workdir\n  - resolve transcript path relative to current dir\n  |\n  v\ncapture(...)\n  - canonicalize transcript path\n  - read transcript snapshot\n  - hash whole source file\n  - parse JSONL transcript\n  - validate transcript cwd is inside repo\n  - derive session_key\n  |\n  v\nGitMetaCaptureInput\n  |\n  v\nwrite_capture(...)\n  - open GitMeta target\n  - read existing dedupe state\n  - append new transcript envelopes\n  - write scalar metadata\n  |\n  v\nCaptureReport\n  |\n  v\nCommandOutput\n```\n\nThe core data shapes relate like this:\n\n```text\nAgent\n  tiny enum: Codex | Claude\n\nParsedTranscript\n  session_id\n  provider\n  model\n  tool_version\n  records: Vec<TranscriptRecord>\n                  |\n                  v\n        TranscriptRecord\n          index\n          source_record_hash\n          normalized fields: timestamp, event kind, role, cwd, ids...\n          source_record: serde_json::Value   <- full parsed provider record\n```\n\nThen capture turns that parsed transcript into the write package:\n\n```text\nParsedTranscript + source file facts + repo validation\n  |\n  v\nGitMetaCaptureInput\n  agent\n  session_key\n  target\n  session_id/provider/model/cwd/tool_version\n  source_path/source_size/source_sha256\n  records: Vec<TranscriptRecord>\n```\n\nAnd GitMeta writes two categories:\n\n```text\nGitMetaCaptureInput\n  |\n  +-- scalar metadata keys\n  |     provider, model, cwd, source-path, source-size, captured-at, etc.\n  |\n  +-- per-record transcript list\n        TranscriptRecord\n          |\n          v\n        TranscriptEnvelope\n          redacted scalar fields\n          redacted source_record\n          source_record_hash\n          source_record_index\n```\n\nThe little `StoredTranscriptEnvelope` type is only for reading old transcript list entries back just far enough to get `source_record_hash` for dedupe. It intentionally does not deserialize the whole envelope.\n\nThe two most important boundaries are:\n\n```text\ntranscript.rs\n  provider-specific parsing:\n  Codex JSONL / Claude JSONL -> common TranscriptRecord shape\n\ngitmeta.rs\n  storage-specific writing:\n  common TranscriptRecord shape -> GitMeta keys/envelopes\n```\n\nSo the mental model is: `cli` deals with command shape, `capture` orchestrates one capture, `transcript` normalizes provider logs, `gitmeta` persists them, and `redaction` is called only when building stored envelopes. The nice thing is that Codex/Claude weirdness is mostly trapped in [transcript.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/transcript.rs:41), while GitMeta mostly sees boring `TranscriptRecord`s.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T22:25:58.127Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}